SIMPLE: warp
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warp
<hw>Warp</hw> <pr>(w⟦add⟧rp)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Warped</conjf> <pr>(w⟦add⟧rpt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Warping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>warpen</ets>; fr. Icel. <ets>varpa</ets> to throw, cast,
<ets>varp</ets> a casting, fr. <ets>verpa</ets> to throw; akin to Dan.
<ets>varpe</ets> to warp a ship, Sw. <ets>varpa</ets>, AS.
<ets>weorpan</ets> to cast, OS. <ets>werpan</ets>, OFries.
<ets>werpa</ets>, D. & LG. <ets>werpen</ets>, G. <ets>werfen</ets>,
Goth. <ets>wa⟦iacute⟧rpan</ets>; cf. Skr. <ets>v⟦rsdot⟧j</ets> to twist.
⟦root⟧144. Cf. <er>Wrap</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw; hence, to send forth, or throw out, as
words; to utter.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Piers
Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To turn or twist out of shape; esp., to twist or
bend out of a flat plane by contraction or otherwise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The planks looked <qex>warped</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Walter <qex>warped</qex> his mouth at this⟦br⟧
To something so mock solemn, that I laughed.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To turn aside from the true direction; to cause to
bend or incline; to pervert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This first avowed, nor folly <qex>warped</qex> my mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have no private considerations to <qex>warp</qex> me in this
controversy.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are divested of all those passions which cloud the intellects,
and <qex>warp</qex> the understandings, of men.</q>
<rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To weave; to fabricate.</def> <mark>[R. &
Poetic.]</mark> <rj><au>Nares.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While doth he mischief <qex>warp</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sternhold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To tow or move, as a vessel, with
a line, or warp, attached to a buoy, anchor, or other fixed
object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To cast prematurely, as young; -- said of cattle,
sheep, etc.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>To let the tide or other water
in upon (lowlying land), for the purpose of fertilization, by a deposit
of warp, or slimy substance.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Rope Making)</fld> <def>To run off the reel into
hauls to be tarred, as yarns.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>To arrange (yarns) on a warp
beam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Aeronautics)</fld> <def>To twist the end surfaces
of (an aerocurve in an airfoil) in order to restore or maintain
equilibrium.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Warped surface</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>a
surface generated by a straight line moving so that no two of its
consecutive positions shall be in the same plane.</cd> <rj><au>Davies &
Peck.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Warp
<hw>Warp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn,
twist, or be twisted out of shape; esp., to be twisted or bent out of a
flat plane; <as>as, a board <ex>warps</ex> in seasoning or
shrinking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of you will prove a shrunk panel, and, like green timber,
<qex>warp</qex>, <qex>warp</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They clamp one piece of wood to the end of another, to keep it
from casting, or <qex>warping</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Moxon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to turn or incline from a straight, true, or proper
course; to deviate; to swerve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is our commission,⟦br⟧
From which we would not have you <qex>warp</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fly with a bending or waving motion; to turn and
wave, like a flock of birds or insects.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pitchy cloud⟦br⟧
Of locusts, <qex>warping</qex> on the eastern wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cast the young prematurely; to slink; -- said of
cattle, sheep, etc.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>To wind yarn off bobbins for
forming the warp of a web; to wind a warp on a warp beam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Warp
<hw>Warp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>wearp</ets>; akin to Icel.
<ets>varp</ets> a casting, throwing, Sw. <ets>varp</ets> the draught of
a net, Dan. <ets>varp</ets> a towline, OHG. <ets>warf</ets> warp, G.
<ets>werft</ets>. See <er>Warp</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>The threads which are extended
lengthwise in the loom, and crossed by the woof.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A rope used in hauling or moving
a vessel, usually with one end attached to an anchor, a post, or other
fixed object; a towing line; a warping hawser.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>A slimy substance deposited on
land by tides, etc., by which a rich alluvial soil is formed.</def>
<rj><au>Lyell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A premature casting of young; -- said of cattle,
sheep, etc.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Four; esp., four herrings; a cast. See
<er>Cast</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 17.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <ety>[From <er>Warp</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>The
state of being warped or twisted; <as>as, the <ex>warp</ex> of a
board</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Warp beam</b></col>, <cd>the roller on which the warp is
wound in a loom.</cd> -- <col><b>Warp fabric</b></col>, <cd>fabric
produced by warp knitting.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Warp frame</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Warp-net frame</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a machine for
making warp lace having a number of needles and employing a thread for
each needle.</cd> -- <col><b>Warp knitting</b></col>, <cd>a kind of
knitting in which a number of threads are interchained each with one or
more contiguous threads on either side; -- also called <cref>warp
weaving</cref>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Warp lace</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Warp net</b></col></mcol>, <cd>lace having a warp crossed by
weft threads.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warpage</ent>⟦br⟧
